Do We Still Have Eden & Old Generation in Recent GC?

This is a VERY GOOD question.

Answer:
👉 It depends on which collector you use.

🟠 Traditional Generational Model (Java 8, 17 default)

Heap structure:

Young Generation
   - Eden
   - Survivor 0
   - Survivor 1

Old Generation

Yes:

Eden exists
Objects age

Promotion to Old Gen
🔵 Modern Low-Latency Collector (Original ZGC)

Originally:
❌ No traditional Eden / Old structure
Heap divided into regions only

Why?
Because it focused on:

Concurrent relocation
Low pause times
Simpler layout

Everything was treated more uniformly.

🟢 But Now (Java 21+ → Generational ZGC)

They reintroduced generational logic.

Because JVM engineers realized:

“Most objects still die young.”

So now:

Yes ✅

There is a Young area concept
There is an Old area concept
But implemented differently using regions

Not fixed blocks like old days.

Instead:

(i)Regions dynamically act as young or old
(ii)Still concurrent
(iii)Still low pause


🧠 So Final Answer
In modern JVM (Java 25):

If using generational collector:
✔️ Young generation exists
✔️ Old generation exists
✔️ Concept of object aging exists

BUT:

Not rigid memory partitions
Region-based
Fully concurrent relocation